        "text": "Education, which also differentiates itself as a closed system […], has to reckon with exactly this. Its address form takes into account the depth of the self-reference of individuals, their freedom, their capacity for self-understanding, their readiness to deviate. Only now educators are taken out of the business of dressage, of the sheer imparting of knowledge for the purposes of a corporative way of life and no longer have to reserve only special attention for (risky) deviations that occur here and there, but fundamentally and always take into account the individuality of the individuals, and just for this it is simply indispensable to have at least one anchor point, the ONE of the person, the minimal unity of the social address of their clientele.\nThus education becomes a tightrope walk between the triviality of pure knowledge transfer and the emerging non-triviality of the social address. On the one hand, the task is to keep trivial machines in operation30 , on the other hand (and increasingly) to de-trivialize trivial machines, i.e. to fit them into the new address form of education31 - a task that, as is easy to understand, can only overtax and eventually drives many who do education professionally into burn-out.\nThe situation becomes disastrous (or less pathetically: extremely complex) when the laborious adjustment of education to the new address format is confronted with the fact that under modern (world) social conditions the address no longer conforms to the image that education has of it in central respects. In other words: The ONE-ness of the address is blown up. It becomes polycontextual, heterarchic, hypercomplex, it takes the form of an inconclusive list. And - horribile dictu -: Education as a functional system of society is directly involved in this process."
